"Fink D., McKelvey B., Hannan D., Newsome D.","Cold rocks, hot sands: In-situ cosmogenic applications in Australia at ANTARES",2000,"Nuclear Instruments and Methods in Physics Research, Section B: Beam Interactions with Materials and Atoms","172","1-4",,"838","846",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0034291897&partnerID=40&md5=2b3333d84d931dcb027188cba85157d5","Physics Division, Australian Nucl. Sci. Technol. O., PMB 1, Menai, NSW 2234, Australia; School of Physical Sciences, University of New England, Armidale, NSW 2351, Australia; School of Applied Science, University of Tasmania, P.O. Box 1214, Launceston, Tasmania 7250, Australia; Department of Environmental Science, Murdoch University, Perth, WA 6150, Australia","Fink, D., Physics Division, Australian Nucl. Sci. Technol. O., PMB 1, Menai, NSW 2234, Australia; McKelvey, B., School of Physical Sciences, University of New England, Armidale, NSW 2351, Australia; Hannan, D., School of Applied Science, University of Tasmania, P.O. Box 1214, Launceston, Tasmania 7250, Australia; Newsome, D., Department of Environmental Science, Murdoch University, Perth, WA 6150, Australia","The ANTARES AMS facility at ANSTO is conducting a comprehensive program in the application of in-situ cosmogenic radionuclides based on strong university collaborations in the earth sciences. The program targets two major objectives: (1) to determine and improve the Quaternary glacial chronology of the Southern Hemisphere in support of global climate change studies; (2) to characterise the processes of surface weathering and landscape evolution in semi-arid regions of the Australian continent. An overview of the program is presented with preliminary results from the first phase of these studies. © 2000 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved.","Cosmogenic isotopes; Glacial chronology; Landscape evolution","Climate change; Geochronology; Geographical regions; Radioisotopes; Rocks; Sand; Weathering; Cosmogenic isotopes; Glacial